The Nasarawa State Office of the Federal Government’s Special Public Works (FGN/SPW) Programme has begun the recruitment of street hawkers and artisans across the state for the 774,000 jobs. The chairman of the Nasarawa State Office of the FGN/SPW Programme, Kasim Mohammed Kasim, led officials in the state for the symbolic recruitment exercise in Akwanga, Nasarawa Eggon and Lafia local government areas. Addressing journalists shortly after carrying out the recruitment exercise in Gudi, Nasarawa Eggon and Lafia towns, Kasim disclosed that two persons were arrested in Akwanga local government area for selling of fake recruitment forms of the programme to unsuspecting members of the public. Kasim, however, assured of his commitment to complying strictly with the instructions of the Minister of State for Labour, Festus Keyamo, who had earlier warned against hijacking of the exercise by politicians. He Said: “Nasarawa State will not differ on the position of the minister, but work in accordance with the mandate of the federal  government in achieving the aims and objectives of the programme.” Kasim also warned that some persons may want to take advantage of the exercise to dupe the public by selling the forms, stressing that the forms are not for sale, and anyone found selling them will be arrested and prosecuted accordingly. Beneficiaries, Zainab Usman and John Maxwell, described the programme as a big step towards improving their means of livelihood. Most of the beneficiaries who were selected for the registration include, young girls hawking at the railway crossing in Gudi, peasant farmers in Mada Station Village, physically challenged beggars at the College of Agriculture Lafia main gate and some laborers at a construction site in Lafia the Nasarawa State capital.